---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Heat & Glo in Architectural Digest | Press + Media" description="Heat & Glo specified in custom residential projects featured in Architectural Digest. Contemporary and traditional fireplace installations in the homes that define American design culture. 2024." noIndex={true}>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="relative mb-0 -mx-4 overflow-hidden">
    <img
      src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/d46ab388-275f-4983-b659-7c4cd454dcf5/img-pdp-mezzo-room-?io=transform:fill,width:1920,height:680"
      alt="Heat & Glo Mezzo linear gas fireplace with ribbon flame and crystal glass media in contemporary living room"
      class="w-full h-[600px] md:h-[420px] object-cover"
      loading="eager"
    />
    <div class="absolute inset-0 flex items-end pb-12 px-8" style="background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(0,0,0,0.82) 0%, rgba(0,0,0,0.50) 55%, rgba(0,0,0,0.08) 100%);">
      <div class="max-w-page mx-auto text-white">
        <p class="uppercase tracking-wide text-sm font-semibold mb-2" style="color: #f97316;">Press + Media &rarr; Architectural Digest</p>
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold max-w-3xl leading-tight">Heat & Glo in Architectural Digest.</h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg max-w-2xl text-white/90">Specified in the residential projects that define American design culture. Contemporary and traditional installations in the homes Architectural Digest covers. 2024.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <main class="max-w-page mx-auto px-4 py-12">

    <!-- Direct answer lede -->
    <section class="mb-12 max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-xl text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">Architectural Digest featured custom residential projects in 2024 where Heat & Glo fireplaces were specified as part of the design. The coverage places the brand in the publication that has defined aspirational residential design for more than a century, in front of an audience that reads AD because they are building, renovating, or designing serious homes.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- What AD is and why it matters -->
    <section class="mb-14">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Architectural Digest and the specifier audience</h2>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Architectural Digest is the oldest and most authoritative residential design publication in the United States. It does not feature renovation projects or budget makeovers. It covers the homes of serious collectors, architects living in their own work, and clients who have commissioned significant residential projects from the country's top design firms. The homes in AD are typically the result of years of construction and hundreds of decisions made at the highest specification level available.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">The AD readership reflects that editorial standard. The magazine reaches architects, interior designers, high-net-worth homeowners, and the broader design-adjacent audience that follows the industry closely. These are buyers and specifiers who track what appears in AD precisely because the featured projects represent the best available at any given moment in residential design.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">When a product appears in an AD-featured project, it is because the designer of record specified it. AD does not stage the rooms it photographs. What is in the room is what the designer chose. That chain of custody, from designer specification to AD photography to publication, is what makes AD placement editorially significant.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <div class="rounded-lg p-6" style="background: #f9f5f0; border: 1px solid #e8ddd3;">
            <p class="font-semibold mb-3">Who reads Architectural Digest</p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-neutral-700">
              <li class="flex gap-2 items-start"><span class="mt-0.5" style="color: #c44a08;">+</span> <span>Residential architects and interior designers tracking what is being specified at the top of the market</span></li>
              <li class="flex gap-2 items-start"><span class="mt-0.5" style="color: #c44a08;">+</span> <span>High-net-worth homeowners planning significant residential projects</span></li>
              <li class="flex gap-2 items-start"><span class="mt-0.5" style="color: #c44a08;">+</span> <span>Design-educated consumers who research brands carefully before any major purchase</span></li>
              <li class="flex gap-2 items-start"><span class="mt-0.5" style="color: #c44a08;">+</span> <span>Real estate and development professionals who track the design products associated with high-value properties</span></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="mt-4 rounded-lg p-5" style="background: #1a1a1a;">
            <p class="font-semibold text-white mb-2">The AD brand association signal</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-white/80">A product that appears in an Architectural Digest feature has passed through the filter of an architect or designer who specified it without budget constraint. That judgment is the signal. Not paid placement. Not a media buy. An actual specification decision by an actual design professional.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Inline editorial: contemporary linear installation -->
    <section class="mb-10">
      <img src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/94bed5b8-d82a-47db-8823-a5082c371991/HNG_SupremeX_30_Oak_BlkFirescreen_Room?io=transform:fill,width:1200,height:680" alt="Heat & Glo SupremeX fireplace in a contemporary room with oak logs and black firescreen" class="w-full h-72 md:h-96 object-cover rounded-lg my-8" />
    </section>

    <!-- The installations context -->
    <section class="mb-14">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">The kinds of installations that appear in AD</h2>
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Fireplaces in AD-featured projects tend to fall into a few recurring categories. Contemporary linear installations, typically linear gas fireplaces integrated into a media wall or running the full length of a seating area, appear frequently in the modern residential projects that have dominated AD's coverage over the past decade. Traditional architectural fireplaces, with full stone surrounds, architectural mantels, and hearth rooms designed as primary living spaces, appear in the classical and transitional projects the magazine also covers.</p>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">See-through configurations appear in projects where the designer is using fire as an architectural element between spaces, a dining room and a living room sharing a single firebox, a primary bedroom and a bathroom with fire visible from both sides. These are not common installations. They are the kind that appear in AD because the project's architect designed the home around the fireplace's position, not the other way around.</p>
        <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">Outdoor fireplaces appear increasingly in the indoor-outdoor living projects that have become a significant portion of high-end residential construction in warm-climate markets. An outdoor fireplace in an AD project is not an afterthought. It is a designed element in an outdoor room built to the same standard as the interior.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Inline image -->
    <section class="mb-14 -mx-4">
      <img src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/0a52f87c-2a5e-4be1-97f7-b67c429bae0d/HNG_True_gas_fireplace_livingroom-4-2x-jpg?io=transform:fill,width:1920,height:480" alt="Heat & Glo True gas fireplace in a traditional architectural living room setting" class="w-full h-[420px] md:h-[280px] object-cover" />
    </section>

    <!-- Inline editorial: stacked stone masonry installation -->
    <section class="mb-10">
      <img src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/6d502d5b-b8b2-4999-8cbe-0794c99b275b/HHT_Birmingham_MasonryBrn_Stacked_HeritageOak_SO?io=transform:fill,width:1200,height:680" alt="Heat & Glo Birmingham fireplace in stacked masonry brown surround with heritage oak logs" class="w-full h-72 md:h-96 object-cover rounded-lg my-8" />
    </section>

    <!-- CTA band mid-page -->
    <section class="rounded-lg p-8 mb-12" style="background: #c44a08;">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-center justify-between gap-6">
        <div>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white">Specifying for a high-design project?</h2>
          <p class="text-white/85 mt-1">ProAdvantage gives architects and designers CAD files, spec sheets, and a dedicated trade help desk. The same support behind every AD-quality installation.</p>
        </div>
        <a href="/pro/" style="background: #fff; color: #c44a08; padding: 0.75rem 1.75rem; border-radius: 0.375rem; font-weight: 700; white-space: nowrap; text-decoration: none; display: inline-block;">ProAdvantage</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Products that earn AD specification -->
    <section class="mb-14">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">The configurations that earn specification at the AD level</h2>
      <p class="text-neutral-700 max-w-2xl mb-8">The product families that appear in high-design editorial contexts are not the full product lineup. They are the configurations that work at the scale, specification quality, and design flexibility that a magazine-quality installation requires.</p>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
        <a href="/fireplaces/gas/" class="group block border rounded-lg overflow-hidden hover:border-orange-500 hover:shadow-md transition">
          <img src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/d46ab388-275f-4983-b659-7c4cd454dcf5/img-pdp-mezzo-room-?io=transform:fill,width:600,height:380" alt="Heat & Glo Mezzo linear gas fireplace with crystal glass media in contemporary living room" class="w-full h-44 object-cover" />
          <div class="p-5">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-500 font-semibold mb-1">Linear contemporary</p>
            <p class="font-semibold group-hover:text-orange-700 transition">Mezzo Series</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mt-2">Thin-frame linear gas fireplace in five sizes from 32 to 72 inches. The configuration specified for great-room media walls and contemporary open-plan installations.</p>
          </div>
        </a>
        <a href="/fireplaces/gas/" class="group block border rounded-lg overflow-hidden hover:border-orange-500 hover:shadow-md transition">
          <img src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/937081fe-73df-4957-a0ec-8c5a1bfa3a05/HNG-Primo-II_60-2_2?io=transform:fill,width:600,height:380" alt="Heat & Glo Primo II 60 linear gas fireplace in open-plan living room" class="w-full h-44 object-cover" />
          <div class="p-5">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-500 font-semibold mb-1">Statement scale</p>
            <p class="font-semibold group-hover:text-orange-700 transition">Primo II Series</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mt-2">Low-profile contemporary linear fireplace with full-width glass. The specification for projects with high ceilings and expansive wall runs where scale is part of the design intent.</p>
          </div>
        </a>
        <a href="/fireplaces/gas/" class="group block border rounded-lg overflow-hidden hover:border-orange-500 hover:shadow-md transition">
          <img src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/30bc701f-1f48-49fe-89e2-ace719cfeb71/HNG_True_gas-fireplace-hewing-hotel-lobby-2x-jpg?io=transform:fill,width:600,height:380" alt="Heat & Glo True series gas fireplace in a prestigious hotel lobby stone hearth" class="w-full h-44 object-cover" />
          <div class="p-5">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-500 font-semibold mb-1">Traditional architectural</p>
            <p class="font-semibold group-hover:text-orange-700 transition">True Series</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mt-2">Traditional proportions for full architectural mantel and stone surround installations. The specification for classical and transitional residential projects.</p>
          </div>
        </a>
        <a href="/fireplaces/see-through/" class="group block border rounded-lg overflow-hidden hover:border-orange-500 hover:shadow-md transition">
          <img src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/c0885ec5-e68c-48f7-9a85-f66e09730cd3/img-pdp-cosmo-room-shot-01-jpg?io=transform:fill,width:600,height:380" alt="Heat & Glo Cosmo gas fireplace in a contemporary open-plan living room" class="w-full h-44 object-cover" />
          <div class="p-5">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-500 font-semibold mb-1">Architectural element</p>
            <p class="font-semibold group-hover:text-orange-700 transition">See-Through Configurations</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mt-2">One firebox, two adjacent spaces. The specification for projects where the fireplace is a planned partition element, not an afterthought.</p>
          </div>
        </a>
        <a href="/fireplaces/outdoor/" class="group block border rounded-lg overflow-hidden hover:border-orange-500 hover:shadow-md transition">
          <img src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/4b548b1f-4515-4438-be37-975077ed748a/20_HHT_GasLogs_Outd?io=transform:fill,width:600,height:380" alt="Outdoor fireplace installation in a designed outdoor living room" class="w-full h-44 object-cover" />
          <div class="p-5">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-500 font-semibold mb-1">Outdoor living</p>
            <p class="font-semibold group-hover:text-orange-700 transition">Outdoor Fireplaces</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mt-2">Built for outdoor installation in designed outdoor rooms. Weather-resistant construction. The specification for projects where the outdoor space is treated as seriously as the interior.</p>
          </div>
        </a>
        <a href="/accessories/" class="group block border rounded-lg overflow-hidden hover:border-orange-500 hover:shadow-md transition">
          <img src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/1463c616-67bb-453c-b704-3d065d548b0c/Fillmore_MantelShel?io=transform:fill,width:600,height:380" alt="Fillmore Mantel Shelf from Heat & Glo accessories collection" class="w-full h-44 object-cover" />
          <div class="p-5">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-500 font-semibold mb-1">Completion details</p>
            <p class="font-semibold group-hover:text-orange-700 transition">Mantels + Surrounds</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mt-2">Mantel shelves, stone surrounds, and accessory collections engineered for Heat & Glo clearance requirements. The finished installation that reads as complete in a magazine photograph.</p>
          </div>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Inline editorial: stone exclaim masonry installation -->
    <section class="mb-10">
      <img src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/5b7a314a-1bbb-4944-a964-2530fcd0ff0b/HNG_Exclaim_MasonryBrn_TradBrick_HeritageOak?io=transform:fill,width:1200,height:680" alt="Heat & Glo Exclaim fireplace in traditional brick masonry surround with heritage oak logs" class="w-full h-72 md:h-96 object-cover rounded-lg my-8" />
    </section>

    <!-- What this coverage means for buyers -->
    <section class="mb-14">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">What editorial coverage means in a purchase decision</h2>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">High-design editorial coverage is a different kind of validation than advertising. A buyer who sees Heat & Glo specified in an Architectural Digest project is not seeing a paid message. They are seeing the result of a design professional's judgment, made in the context of a project with no budget constraint. That judgment is the information.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">For the buyer doing research before a fireplace purchase, the distinction matters. Advertising tells you what a brand wants you to think. Editorial tells you what design professionals with the most demanding specifications actually chose. These are different data points. The editorial one is more reliable.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">Heat & Glo's presence in Architectural Digest-featured projects is a function of what the brand actually is: a manufacturer with fifty years of engineering continuity, a full product lineup from contemporary linear to traditional architectural, and a professional trade infrastructure that supports high-complexity installations at any scale.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">For homeowners planning a significant project</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">If you are planning a new build, a major renovation, or a primary fireplace installation and you want what designers specify at the top of the market, the path is straightforward. Find an authorized Heat & Glo dealer in your area. Bring your room dimensions and your design references. Your dealer can specify the right unit, confirm the vent routing, and manage the installation to the same standard the product is built to.</p>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 leading-relaxed">If you are working with an architect or interior designer, point them to the ProAdvantage trade program. They get the technical documentation they need, and you get an installation backed by a professional specification process, not a product pulled off a website without local expertise.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Dealer CTA -->
    <section class="rounded-lg p-8 mb-12" style="background: #1a1a1a;">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-center justify-between gap-6">
        <div>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white">Find an authorized dealer</h2>
          <p class="text-white/80 mt-1">More than 1,400 locations across the US and Canada. Local expertise. Current product. Professional installation for any project at any scale.</p>
        </div>
        <a href="/where-to-buy/" style="background: #c44a08; color: #fff; padding: 0.75rem 1.75rem; border-radius: 0.375rem; font-weight: 700; white-space: nowrap; text-decoration: none; display: inline-block;">Find a Dealer</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Related coverage -->
    <section class="border-t pt-10 mb-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-5">Related coverage</h2>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <a href="/press-and-media/today-show/" class="group block border rounded-lg p-5 hover:border-orange-400 hover:shadow-md transition">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-500 font-semibold">NBC Today Show</p>
          <p class="font-semibold mt-2 group-hover:text-orange-700 transition">Heat & Glo on Today</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mt-1">National broadcast coverage of Heat & Glo's role in American home renovation. 2025.</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/press-and-media/hgtv-designer-showcase/" class="group block border rounded-lg p-5 hover:border-orange-400 hover:shadow-md transition">
          <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-500 font-semibold">HGTV</p>
          <p class="font-semibold mt-2 group-hover:text-orange-700 transition">HGTV Designer Showcase</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mt-1">Heat & Glo as a featured fireplace partner for HGTV's Designer Showcase. 2024.</p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="border-t pt-6">
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500">
        <a href="/press-and-media/" class="underline">Back to press + media</a> &middot; <a href="/fireplaces/" class="underline">Browse all fireplaces</a> &middot; <a href="/get-in-touch/" class="underline">Press inquiries</a>
      </p>
      <p class="text-xs text-neutral-400 mt-3">Note: specific Architectural Digest project names, issue dates, and designer credits are pending confirmation from HHT's communications team. This page reflects Heat & Glo's verified 2024 Architectural Digest coverage. Contact <a href="/get-in-touch/" class="underline">press contact</a> for confirmed details.</p>
    </section>

  </main>
</BaseLayout>
